ntenelle describes the new cosmology of the Copernican world view with matchles clarity, imagination, and wit. Moreover, he boldly makes his interlocutor a woman, inviting female participation in the almost exclusively male province of scientific discourse. The popular Fontenelle lived through an entire century, from 1657 to 1757, and wrote prolifically. H. A. Hargreaves's fresh, appealing translation brings the author's masterpiece to new generations of readers, while the introduction by Nina Rattner Gelbart clearly demonstrates the importance of the Conversations for the history of science, of women, of literature, and of French civilization, and for the popularization of culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPlurality of worldsvEarly works to 1800. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520910584.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles